India’s January Oil-Product Sales Rise 5.9% as Economy Expands

-- B y   A r c h a n a   C h a u d h a r y
-- 
2011-02-24T10:18:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-24/india-s-january-oil-product-sales-rise-5-9-as-economy-expands.html
  India ’s oil-product sales in January
rose to the second-highest this fiscal year as users in the
world’s second-fastest growing major economy bought more diesel
and gasoline to fuel vehicles and factories.  Sales climbed 5.9 percent from a year earlier to 12.3
million metric tons, according to preliminary government data.
Volume reached 12.9 million tons in December, the highest in the
year to March. Diesel, which accounts for about 40 percent of
fuel sales, increased 6.4 percent to 4.99 million tons. Gasoline
sales gained 8.9 percent to 1.14 million tons.  Power companies including the nation’s largest generator,
NTPC Ltd., and vehicle makers are adding capacity in India,
boosting fuel sales. The government estimated on Feb. 7 that the
$1.3 trillion economy may grow 8.6 percent in the year ending
March 31, the highest rate since 2008.  Sales of liquefied natural gas climbed 34 percent to
817,200 tons, while naphtha, used as chemical feedstock, rose
4.5 percent to 805,200 tons.  Jet-fuel sales increased 12 percent to 446,500 tons and
liquefied petroleum gas, used as cooking fuel and to power
vehicles, grew 9.1 percent to 1.24 million tons.  Sales of kerosene declined 1 percent to 762,800 tons.
Bitumen, used in  road construction , dropped 9.3 percent to
423,300 tons.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Archana Chaudhary in  New Delhi  at 
 achaudhary2@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Stephen Foxwell at   sfoxwell@bloomberg.net . 